Content Approach: Competitors are either (a) listicle galleries with minimal decision guidance — lots of images, shallow copy — or (b) brand-driven posts pushing specific product ranges. The gap is clear: nobody helps brides understand how a color will actually look in photographs, and nobody builds a decision framework around the three variables that actually matter — dress undertone, skin undertone, and lighting conditions. Most posts treat color as a purely aesthetic choice, not a photography performance choice.

Visual Patterns: 10–15 images typical. Heavy on swatches and nail close-ups. Strong Pinterest-style gallery format is standard.

Recommended Image Count: 10–12. Gallery-format expectations are high for this topic. Prioritise: close-up ring shots showing color against skin, at least two skin tone variations per major colour family, and one or two "how it looks in natural vs reception light" comparisons if available.

Competitor Gaps — Unanswered Questions:
- "Will this color look different in my wedding photos vs in real life?"
