AUDIENCE INTELLIGENCE

Blog Gen Instruction: This section is your primary creative brief. Use this audience data to inform every paragraph, sentence, and word choice. You are writing for this specific person with this specific intent. Satisfy them completely.

Who They Are: Brides primarily 25–38 who have the dress sorted and are now making nail decisions. Some are regular salon clients; many are not. Significant cohort are anxious about looking "wrong" in photos — they know their nails will be photographed and that's the main anxiety driving the search. Global Tier 1. Secondary audience: bridesmaids and mothers-of-the-bride looking for guidance.

What They Want From This Post: To understand which colors will look beautiful in photographs — not just in the mirror. Specifically: which shade suits their skin tone, coordinates with their dress, and won't compete with their ring. They want concrete guidance, not a gallery of 40 identical blush nails.

What Satisfies Them: A decision framework they can actually use, with specific shade descriptions and photography notes per color. Acknowledgment that skin tone and dress undertone matter differently. Clear guidance on what to ask for at the salon. Validation that non-traditional choices (sage, lavender, terracotta) can work.

What Frustrates Them: Generic advice like "any nude will work" without specifying which nude for which undertone. Posts that show only white/pink/nude without acknowledging the growing palette of 2026 bridal options. No guidance on how colors photograph vs how they look in person. Recommendations dominated by one skin tone representation.

